Good question — this is exactly the kind of thing that trips people up in real deployments.

🧠 Short Answer

Yes — for the remote server, you can run:

sudo usermod -aG docker ec2-user

from Jenkins via SSH.

But there’s an important catch 👇

⚠️ The Gotcha (Very Important)

After running:

usermod -aG docker ec2-user

👉 The change does NOT apply immediately to the current SSH session.

So if you do this inside Jenkins and then run:

docker ps

❌ It may still fail with permission denied.

✅ Recommended Approaches
✅ Option 1 (Simplest): Just use sudo docker

This is what you're already doing — and it's perfectly fine:

sudo docker run ...

✔ No need to modify user groups
✔ Works immediately
✔ Best for CI/CD pipelines

👉 This is the safest and most common approach

✅ Option 2: Add user to docker group (one-time setup)

Run this once manually (or via Jenkins setup stage):

sudo usermod -aG docker ec2-user

Then either:

Log out & log back in
OR restart the instance

After that:

docker run ...

(no sudo needed)

⚠️ If you try inside Jenkins

Even if you do:

sudo usermod -aG docker ec2-user
newgrp docker

👉 It usually won’t persist properly in non-interactive SSH sessions.

🚀 Best Practice for Your Pipeline

Keep it simple:

sudo docker ...

✔ No permission issues
✔ No session problems
✔ Works reliably in Jenkins

🔥 Pro Tip

If you want cleaner commands without sudo, use:

sudo su - ec2-user -c "docker ps"

But honestly — not necessary.

✅ Final Recommendation

👉 For local Jenkins machine:

sudo usermod -aG docker jenkins

👉 For remote EC2:

Either:
Run once manually
OR just use:
sudo docker ...

✔ I strongly recommend sticking with sudo docker in pipelines.

If you want, I can:

Add a one-time remote setup stage
Or make your pipeline idempotent (auto-configures server cleanly)